{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"233932cb-1416-412c-b5cd-911e885b9603","content":"In VS Code, create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- The server communicates over **stdio** (stdin/stdout).\n- `dotnet run --project` builds and launches your server.\n- Once saved, VS Code Copilot agent mode will detect and connect to it automatically.\n\nIf you've published a standalone executable instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to your binary. You can also add `\"env\": {}` for environment variables your server needs.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fbf0e7cd-a6fb-4d93-a0f8-d779b4c18f06","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":268,"requestId":"201D:3DEB8E:1C120C9:1F19B28:6A0521F1"},"id":"3b787e4d-4f1e-4f61-8b2d-2ef2572502b3","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:14:32.551Z","parentId":"a493ef9c-fac8-4cad-9aa8-e69f01af117c"}
